Hi, thank you for your suggestion, this should be put in the wish list.
However I think that there is a way that this could be achieve now (waiting for a more comprehensive implementation.
Let me explain:
in the read operation , there is a need to fetch a fresh value of the variable asynchronously and wait for the callback to be called prior to returning the requested node value in the opcua request.
However, in the write operation we could imagine that the opcua write request simply initiates an asynchronous write operation and returns immediately without waiting for the asynchronous write op to be completed.

In this case the code would look like:

```javascript
  server.engine.addVariableInFolder(myDevices, {
        browseName: "Temperature",
        nodeId: "ns=2;s=Temperature",
        dataType: "Double",

        value: {
            refreshFunc: function (callback) {

                var temperature = 20 + 10 * Math.sin(Date.now() / 10000);
                var value = new Variant({dataType: DataType.Double, value: temperature});
                var sourceTimestamp = new Date();

                // simulate a asynchronous behaviour
                setTimeout(function () {
                    callback(null, value, sourceTimestamp);
                }, 100);
            }
            set: function(value) {
                  startAsyncWrite(value,function unused_callback(err,data){});
            }
        }
    });
```

Thanks Etienne, however our requirements mandate that we get a confirmation from the wireless endpoint when the write was successfully received and processed (for critical control outputs).

Would you entertain the thought of adding a similar "refreshWriteFunc" capability to the OPCUA server:


// write services
OPCUAServer.prototype._on_WriteRequest = function (message, channel) {

    var server = this;

    var request = message.request;
    assert(request instanceof WriteRequest);
    assert(_.isArray(request.nodesToWrite));

    var results = [];

        assert(request.nodesToWrite[0]._schema.name === "WriteValue");
        results = server.engine.write(request.nodesToWrite);

    server.engine.refreshWriteValues(request.nodesToWrite,function(err,data){
         assert(_.isArray(results));
         assert(results.length === request.nodesToWrite.length);

	    var response = new WriteResponse({
		   results: results,
		   diagnosticInfos: null
	    });
	    channel.send_response("MSG", response, message);

    });

};


This refreshWriteFunc would also need to allow the return of response codes (like errors) to override the response code that was returned from the simple set function.  We would then relabel the existing refresh function as "refreshReadFunc" to separate them.  Please let me know your thoughts, and I would be willing to make the changes if you would like.  Thanks so much.

The `rotate()` from #34 is very useful, however I think the implementation may have missed a case: `extract()` gets the same pixels before a `rotate()` as after. Reading the docs, it does only say that pre/post `resize()` would matter, but I think it's fair to expect that someone would want pre/post `rotate()` as well.

Sample code:
```
  var e = sharp(imagePath)
  	.rotate(img.rotation)
//        .resize(img.masterWidth, img.masterHeight)
        .extract(region.top, region.left, region.width, region.height);
  console.log('extract options', e.options);
  e
    .toFile(output);
```

If you run this without the `resize()` you'll see that the extract options have Pre offsets, even though it's chained after the rotation. (Moving `extract()` before the rotation gives the same output.) A work-around is to resize to the full dimensions before the extract.

