@ErisDS One pattern than I've seen a number of times (which I can't remember where) is that your app emits events at various points during startup. You then initialize the bank of modules that you'll need, passing in the app to each (in a constructor or factory, whatever). The module then simply wires up what it needs to do when the app emits certain events.

The hard part here is knowing when these events are finished and when the app can start. Usually it's OK to have these things fire up asyncronously - in other words *is it really necessary to wire up the mail engine and then move on?* - probably not. So, you do the necessaries: load up the middleware, fire up the DB and then start the app.

This has the major benefit of allowing extensibility in the future with modules you add in.

