@ErisDS So my answer above is basically "Yes" - with EventEmitter it's quite easy and extensible to wire things, but sometimes not completely obvious. Here's an example in pseudo-code:

```javascript
var app = express();
app.emit("instantiated");
//we need some data
var DB = require("./lib/db");
//instance the db and
//connect it
app.db = DB.connect(app, connectionString);
```

The only thing we'll probably need right away is to know the DB is connected and we can have the DB module tell us that's the case:

```javascript
var DB = function(){
  var db = {};
  db.connect = function(app, connectionString){
    //psuedo connection code
    client.connect(connectionString, function(err,dbInstance)){
      app.db = dbInstance;
      app.emit("db-connected");
    };
  }
  return db;
}

module.exports = DB;
```

in our app.js bootstrapper we can listen for this event:

```javascript
app.on("db-connected", function(){
  //we have a db instance on app, so let's do whatever else we need!
  app.mailer = require("./lib/mailer").load(app);
  app.auth = require("./lib/authentication).load(app);
});
```

In this case we have an open DB connection so we're good to go. The only thing I can think of that might need to be done that takes a while is the update check - but that can be handled using sockets and it really doesn't need to go off during startup. 

