The reason that this is happening is that `then` will keep resolve its arguments until it is no longer a promise. 

In your case where you wrapped the ElementFinder (which is a promise) in a promise, webdriver will first resolve the outer promise. Then seeing the ElementFinder is also a promise, resolve that as well, resulting in the failure. There is no way to tell `then` to only resolve once. 

```javascript
it('error', function(){
      var el1 = element(by.xpath('//bar')); //this is a promise
      var el2 = protractor.promise.fulfilled(el1); //this is also a promise
      el1.then() //this resolves the promise and results in an ElementNotFound exception
      el2.then() //this resolves the outer promise, which is fine, but also tries to resolve e1, which causes the same exception
});
```

Note that there isn't any way to make this nicer, because as part of protractor's API contract:
```javascript
elementFinder.then(function(e) {
  //e should be a raw web element, and has to throw ElementNotFound.
})
```

Of course we can break this contract in a breaking change, which I am supportive of because people make lots of mistakes with this (see below for example), but that's a separate discussion. 

All in all, you should never wrap ElementFinder in a promise, because that's a recipe to failure and flakiness. Imagine this:

```javascript
var el1 = element(by.css('some_valid_css'));
var promise = protractor.promise.fulfilled(el1);
promise.then(function(elementFinder){
    elementFinder.click();
    expect(elementFinder.getText()).toEqual('some value');
});
```

Many people erroneously think the above is equivalent to:
```javascript
var el1 = element(by.css('some_valid_css'));
el1.click();
expect(el1.getText()).toEqual('some value');
```

But that's not the case because in the first snippet, `elementFinder` is actually not an element finder, but a raw webelement resolved from `el1`. The result? If your `click()` performs some action, nothing is synced and you will get flake.

