I'm not sure I understand the concern. These aren't "internal" variables - they came FROM the very same config that onPrepare() is being executed in. It's not passing `this` (which has driverprovider and all sorts of things)... just `config`:

```javascript
var Runner = function(config) {    /// <------ I give you the config in the first place...
  log.set(config);
  this.preparer_ = null;
  this.driverprovider_ = null;
  this.config_ = config;                   /// <----- You're just giving it back as a convenience...
  // ...
};
```

The only vars in that block that don't come from the caller are:

```javascript
     // The CURRENT capabilities being run
    capabilities: {},
    // The command used to start Protractor
    '$0': 'node ./node_modules/protractor/bin/protractor',
    // An array of args used to start Protractor
    _: [ 'test-client/protractor.conf.js' ],
    // ... There may be an additional var or two depending on how the Selenium config was interpreted
```

I would still argue that these additional vars are useful. onPrepare()'s purpose is very well aligned with the need for these variables. To do anything context-sensitive when you aren't using `multiCapabilities` you need to take an internal reference to your own config object before you export it. It's just a sensible convenience to pass it back for that case. That's especially valuable when onPrepare is an external script - a nice feature added recently but it's super awkward to pass config data to it...

Finally, I would argue that multiple configs is a terrible answer. This whole `multiCapabilities` feature must have been added for a reason, but there are half a dozen issues posted over the last year asking how to do things with it where the answer was "sorry, you can't, use multiple configs". When it comes down to the trade-offs, what advantage does Protractor gain by NOT making this easier in exchange for avoiding the perceived risk of... making this easier?

Does there have to be a specific opt-in? Or can written such that opts are only passed to the render separately if they're detected? (https://github.com/mde/ejs/blob/master/lib/ejs.js#L189)

With an API where there are two optional args of the same type, you have to make one of them take precedence anyhow -- i.e., to pass opts and no actual data, you have to pass an empty data object:

```javascript
render('foo.ejs', {bar: 'baz'}, {cache: true});
render('foo.ejs', {bar: 'baz'});
render('foo.ejs', {}, {cache: true});
```

@TimothyGu, `renderFile` ultimately passes off to `render`, which handles the mixin bit.

@dougwilson, I was suggesting Express could handle the mixing-in part if needed at its level, the way that EJS currently does -- if it detects a single object, takes the empty options object created by default and copies any option keys in the data object over to it. This allows people consuming the Express `render` API to use either method signature for a version, but your code underneath it to always expect separate data and options. Then once there's enough code around using the new API, you can remove the shim in a future version.

And I'm not sure what API you're thinking of for passing the locals vs. opts, but some of the changes I wanted to make here were driven by the idea of making this implementation conform more to the usual API for EJS (given that there are other implementations that have been around for a long time), and for similar template languages like ERB. I'm a fan of the Principle of Least Surprise, and letting people transfer as much knowledge from one similar area to the other.

This is a long-winded way of saying that having a "locals" key for the local vars subsumed in an options object is different from the way all similar systems behave, which is why I went with a (data, opts) signature. There are lots of people using EJS outside Express, and it should be the same API no matter where you go. I hope that makes sense.

