It's reliable to set `process.env.TZ` provided that you do it just once and do so before other time-zone related code runs. That is what I've done here, and is what I have been successfully in our app in production for months. We develop in Eastern, run our servers in UTC but our app is deployed to serve   users in four time zones currently. 

Declaring UTC as a default once at the very beginning of processing is less error-prone than remembering to explicitly declare UTC at every point in the code that processes code. 

To try reproduce the test failure without the patch, try this:

    TZ="America/New_York" grunt test-unit

You also try try modifying my patch to set `process.env.TZ="America/New_York"` as well.

If you instead go the route of assuming that the Markdown files you are imported have UTC times in the filename then that should be mentioned in the import docs as part of the "spec" of the importer. If third-parties are generating data to match this spec, that's an important detail to know.

